Here's how to handle all three requirements:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation + confirm dialog**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page's code-behind:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget since the override is synchronous
            ConfirmDiscardChanges();
            return true; // cancel the default navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async void ConfirmDiscardChanges()
    {
        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (discard)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

> ⚠️ `OnBackButtonPressed` only fires for the **hardware/system back button** (Android, desktop). It does **not** fire when the user taps the Shell navigation bar's back arrow.

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button (catches the nav-bar arrow too)**

Use `BackButtonBehavior` in your XAML to replace the arrow with a "Cancel" button that routes through the same confirmation logic:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

Then in your ViewModel (or code-behind):

```csharp
public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

public EditProductViewModel()
{
    BackCommand = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard) return;
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });
}
```

**Summary:** You need both mechanisms — `OnBackButtonPressed` for the system back button and `BackButtonBehavior` for the shell nav-bar. The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the default arrow tap entirely, so your confirmation logic covers both paths.
